A Single Geometric Measure for Elasticity of Demand and Supply
Letter to the Editor—Graphical Selection of Military Supply Tables
items.abstract: <jats:p> The writer has had occasion to make certain of the computations referred to in Geisler and Karr's paper on “The Design of Military Supply Tables for Spare Parts,” published in the August 1956 issue of the Journal (vol. 4, pp. 431–442). A somewhat unusual graphical method of making the trial and error computation discussed as Method I of the paper was devised and found to reduce considerably the amount of labor required for the computation. The graphical method is the subject of this letter. </jats:p>

title: Review of the soap association's research activities pertaining to water supply and sewage treatment
container-title: Journal of the American Oil Chemists' Society
items.abstract: <jats:title>Conclusion</jats:title><jats:p>In conclusion, the Soap Association's research program to data, in addition to contributing to the technical knowledge, has had very constructive effects in at least two somewhat separate but important areas. First, the research program has corrected a number of misconceptions about the possible effects of the normal use of household detergents by the American public on water supplies and sewage treatement misconceptions which otherwise might have been accepted by default; and second, it seems reasonable to assume from the findings so far that it will be possible, if necessary, to develop technological processes capable of handling any problems which may arise.</jats:p>
